{"title_page": "Sweden national under-19 basketball team", "text_new": "{{Infobox national basketball team\n| country            = Sweden \n| logo               = Flag of Sweden.svg\n| logo_width         = 130px \n| nickname           = ''Bl\u00e5gult''<br>(The Blue and Yellow)\n| fiba_zone          = FIBA Europe\n| national_fed       = [[Swedish Basketball Federation|Svenska Basketbollf\u00f6rbundet]] \n| coach              = \n| wc_championship    = [[FIBA Under-19 Basketball World Cup|Under-19 World Cup]]\n| wc_appearances     = None\n| wc_medals          = \n| zone_championship  = [[FIBA U18 European Championship|U18 European Championship]]\n| zone_appearances   = 7\n| zone_medals        = None\n| zone_championship2 = [[FIBA U18 European Championship#Division B|U18 European Championship Division B]]\n| zone_appearances2  = 13\n| zone_medals2       = {{Eur1}} ''Gold:'' ([[2009 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2009]], [[2015 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2015]])<br>{{Eur3}} ''Bronze:'' ([[2011 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2011]])\n| h_pattern_b        = _bluesides\n| h_body             = FAD201\n| h_shorts           = FAD201\n| h_pattern_s        = _bluesides\n| a_pattern_b        = _goldsides\n| a_body             = 0000FF\n| a_shorts           = 0000FF\n| a_pattern_s        = _goldsides \n}}\n\nThe '''Sweden national under-18 and under-19 basketball team''' ({{lang-sv|svenska juniorlandslaget i basket}}) is the national representative for [[Sweden]] in international under-18 and under-19 [[basketball]] competitions. They are controlled by the [[Swedish Basketball Federation|Svenska Basketbollf\u00f6rbundet]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sweden (U18-U19)|url=https://www.eurobasket.com/Sweden/basketball-National-Team.asp?Age=18|accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref> The team competes at the [[FIBA U18 European Championship]], with the opportunity to qualify for the [[FIBA Under-19 Basketball World Cup|FIBA Under-19 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sweden at the 2016 FIBA U18 European Championship|url=https://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u18/2016/Sweden|accessdate=22 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sweden at the 2017 FIBA U16 European Championship Division B|url=https://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u18b/2017/Sweden|accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sweden at the 2018 FIBA U18 European Championship Division B|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u18b/2018/team/Sweden|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sweden at the 2019 FIBA U18 European Championship Division B|url=https://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u18b/2019/team/Sweden|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nSweden won their first gold medal at the [[2009 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2009 U18 European Championship Division B]], and won their second in [[2015 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2015]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sweden national basketball team]]\n*[[Sweden national under-17 basketball team]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.basket.se/ Official website] {{in lang|sv}}\n*[http://www.fiba.basketball/federation/Sweden FIBA profile]\n\n{{International youth basketball}}\n{{National sports teams of Sweden}}\n\n[[Category:National sports teams of Sweden]]\n[[Category:National under-18 basketball teams]]\n[[Category:National under-19 basketball teams]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox national basketball team\n| country            = Sweden \n| logo               = Flag of Sweden.svg\n| logo_width         = 130px \n| nickname           = ''Bl\u00e5gult''<br>(The Blue and Yellow)\n| fiba_zone          = FIBA Europe\n| national_fed       = [[Swedish Basketball Federation|Svenska Basketbollf\u00f6rbundet]] \n| coach              = \n| wc_championship    = [[FIBA Under-19 Basketball World Cup|Under-19 World Cup]]\n| wc_appearances     = None\n| wc_medals          = \n| zone_championship  = [[FIBA U18 European Championship|U18 European Championship]]\n| zone_appearances   = 7\n| zone_medals        = None\n| zone_championship2 = [[FIBA U18 European Championship#Division B|U18 European Championship Division B]]\n| zone_appearances2  = 13\n| zone_medals2       = {{Eur1}} ''Gold:'' ([[2009 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2009]], [[2015 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2015]])<br>{{Eur3}} ''Bronze:'' ([[2011 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2011]])\n| h_pattern_b        = _bluesides\n| h_body             = FAD201\n| h_shorts           = FAD201\n| h_pattern_s        = _bluesides\n| a_pattern_b        = _goldsides\n| a_body             = 0000FF\n| a_shorts           = 0000FF\n| a_pattern_s        = _goldsides \n}}\n\nThe '''Sweden national under-18 and under-19 basketball team''' ({{lang-sv|svenska juniorlandslaget i basket}}) is the national representative for [[Sweden]] in international under-18 and under-19 [[basketball]] competitions. They are controlled by the [[Swedish Basketball Federation|Svenska Basketbollf\u00f6rbundet]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sweden (U18-U19)|url=https://www.eurobasket.com/Sweden/basketball-National-Team.asp?Age=18|accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref> The team competes at the [[FIBA U18 European Championship]], with the opportunity to qualify for the [[FIBA Under-19 Basketball World Cup|FIBA Under-19 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sweden at the 2016 FIBA U18 European Championship|url=https://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u18/2016/Sweden|accessdate=22 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sweden at the 2017 FIBA U16 European Championship Division B|url=https://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u18b/2017/Sweden|accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nSweden won their first gold medal at the [[2009 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2009 U18 European Championship Division B]], and won their second in [[2015 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship Division B|2015]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sweden national basketball team]]\n*[[Sweden national under-17 basketball team]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.basket.se/ Official website] {{in lang|sv}}\n*[http://www.fiba.basketball/federation/Sweden FIBA profile]\n\n{{International youth basketball}}\n{{National sports teams of Sweden}}\n\n[[Category:National sports teams of Sweden]]\n[[Category:National under-18 basketball teams]]\n[[Category:National under-19 basketball teams]]\n", "name_user": "SpinnDoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweden_national_under-19_basketball_team"}
{"title_page": "Liam Stapleton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Liam Stapleton\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth based on age as of date |21 |2017|November|22}}\n| birth_place        = \n| home_town          = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]\n| death_date         = \n| height             = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Australian\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Radio presenter, comedian\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = punching billies and sinkin tinnies \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n'''Liam Stapleton''' co-hosts the Breakfast show on [[Nova 919]] with [[Ben Harvey, that dude that was repeatedly seen walking his cat on an actual leash (Australian radio personality)|Ben Harvey]].\n\n== Early life ==\nStapleton grew up in the suburbs of Adelaide.<ref name=\"pedestrian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/music/heres-what-we-know-about-triple-js-new-brekkie-boys-ben-liam/ |title=Here\u2019s What We Know About Triple J\u2019s New \u2018Brekkie\u2019 Boys Ben & Liam |work=Pedestrian TV |date=22 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nStapleton began his radio career aged 14 years old at the Adelaide [[community radio]] station [[Fresh 92.7]], where he met Ben Harvey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/radio/meet-the-new-hosts-of-the-triple-j-brekky-show/news-story/06c5c762962a96cbd9a0525b886304b3 |title=Meet the new hosts of the Triple J brekky show |work=news.com.au |last=Bucklow |first=Andrew |date=22 November 2016}}</ref> As a duo, \"[[Ben & Liam]]\" went on to present the breakfast show for Fresh 92.7, compete in the state finals of [[Raw Comedy]], and host a comedy show at the [[Adelaide Fringe Festival]].<ref name=\"pedestrian\" />\n\nIn late 2016, Harvey and Stapleton were confirmed to take over from [[Matt Okine]] and [[Alex Dyson]] as co-hosts of the nationwide [[Triple J]] Breakfast show in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mediaweek.com.au/prime7-win-collignon-heatley-lauri/ |title=Triple j\u2019s Ben & Liam: From local radio to national breakfast show |work=Media Week |last=Joshi |first=Kruti |date=2 February 2017}}</ref> They were signed on for another year in the role in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiotoday.com.au/adelaide-australia-making-triple-js-ben-liam/ |title=From Adelaide to Australia, the making of triple j\u2019s Ben & Liam |work=Radio Today |last=Challenor |first=Jake |date=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Triple J}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stapleton, Liam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Australian male comedians]]\n[[Category:Triple J announcers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{Australia-radio-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Liam Stapleton\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth based on age as of date |21 |2017|November|22}}\n| birth_place        = \n| home_town          = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]\n| death_date         = \n| height             = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Australian\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Radio presenter, comedian\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n'''Liam Stapleton''' co-hosts the Breakfast show on [[Nova 919]] with [[Ben Harvey (Australian radio personality)|Ben Harvey]].\n\n== Early life ==\nStapleton grew up in the suburbs of Adelaide.<ref name=\"pedestrian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pedestrian.tv/music/heres-what-we-know-about-triple-js-new-brekkie-boys-ben-liam/ |title=Here\u2019s What We Know About Triple J\u2019s New \u2018Brekkie\u2019 Boys Ben & Liam |work=Pedestrian TV |date=22 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nStapleton began his radio career aged 14 years old at the Adelaide [[community radio]] station [[Fresh 92.7]], where he met Ben Harvey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/radio/meet-the-new-hosts-of-the-triple-j-brekky-show/news-story/06c5c762962a96cbd9a0525b886304b3 |title=Meet the new hosts of the Triple J brekky show |work=news.com.au |last=Bucklow |first=Andrew |date=22 November 2016}}</ref> As a duo, \"[[Ben & Liam]]\" went on to present the breakfast show for Fresh 92.7, compete in the state finals of [[Raw Comedy]], and host a comedy show at the [[Adelaide Fringe Festival]].<ref name=\"pedestrian\" />\n\nIn late 2016, Harvey and Stapleton were confirmed to take over from [[Matt Okine]] and [[Alex Dyson]] as co-hosts of the nationwide [[Triple J]] Breakfast show in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mediaweek.com.au/prime7-win-collignon-heatley-lauri/ |title=Triple j\u2019s Ben & Liam: From local radio to national breakfast show |work=Media Week |last=Joshi |first=Kruti |date=2 February 2017}}</ref> They were signed on for another year in the role in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiotoday.com.au/adelaide-australia-making-triple-js-ben-liam/ |title=From Adelaide to Australia, the making of triple j\u2019s Ben & Liam |work=Radio Today |last=Challenor |first=Jake |date=15 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Triple J}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stapleton, Liam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Australian male comedians]]\n[[Category:Triple J announcers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{Australia-radio-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2001:8004:2720:3c3e:c50e:92ee:aedd:792b", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Added content, corrected content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liam_Stapleton"}
{"title_page": "The Night Watch (Waters novel)", "text_new": "{{short description|2006 historical fiction novel}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The Night Watch\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = TheNightWatchcover2006.jpg\n| caption       = UK first edition cover\n| author        = [[Sarah Waters]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  = TWBG - Duncan Spilling<br>Lettering: Stephen Raw\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Historical fiction]]\n| publisher     = Virago\n| release_date  = 2 Feb 2006 (UK)\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages         = 480 pp\n| isbn          = 1-84408-246-6\n| oclc= 62265716\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''The Night Watch''''' is a dark, 2006 [[historical fiction]] novel by  [[Sarah Waters]]. It was shortlisted for both the 2006 [[Man Booker Prize]] and the 2006 [[Orange Prize]]. The novel, which is [[Reverse chronology|told backward]] through third-person narrative, takes place in 1940s London during and after [[World War II]]. The storyline follows the fragmented lives and the strange interconnections between Kay, Helen and Julia, three lesbians; Viv, a straight woman; and Duncan, her brother, whose sexuality is ambiguous. The war, with its never-ending night watches, serves as a horrifying context, backdrop and metaphor as a constant reminder of the morbidity that surrounds life and love.\n\n==Plot summary==\n{{Plot|date=November 2008}}\n\n===1947===\n'''Kay'''\n\nThe novel begins with Kay Langrish-a woman broken by the war. She spends her days locked in her room in London, watching her landlord's patients arrive and leave at precisely the same hours every day.   The only human contact that Kay is seen to be having at this stage in the narrative is with another lesbian, Mickey.  Kay is suggested to be wealthy by her residence in [[Lavender Hill]].  One night, while waiting for the cinema doors to open, Viv, a woman from her past appears and hands to her a gold ring.  \n\n'''Helen'''\n\nHelen and her assistant Viv run a match-making agency near [[Bond Street]] for individuals who have either lost their loved one or were disappointed to see how much their sweethearts had changed after the war.  The work itself is not very fulfilling, but their hesitant friendship keeps them entertained.\n\n'''Viv'''\n\nAfter work, Viv sets off to meet her brother Duncan, who lives with a much older gentleman named Mr Mundy.  The three of them meet on a weekly basis for dinner at Mr Mundy's, and Viv always brings a tin of meat for them to share.   Duncan shrugs off news of their father, and proceeds to show Viv the latest addition to his antiques collection.  Viv politely ends the night and heads for the railway station, but she doesn't go home to her father's.  \n\nOn the same day that Helen wanted to confide her love for Julia to Viv, the two women receive an unexpected visit from Robert Fraser, Duncan\u2019s old cellmate.  He asks to speak with her regarding Duncan, and his present condition: collecting antiques (which Robert finds morbid), living with Mr Mundy, whom both men knew at the prison, and working at a candle factory.  Viv dismisses Fraser, feeling as though he thinks she and her father haven\u2019t done enough to help Duncan\u2019s situation and explains that he simply doesn\u2019t know everything.\n  \n'''Duncan'''\n\nDuncan accompanies Mr Mundy, or \"Uncle Horace,\" as he referred to him in public, every Tuesday to his [[Christian Science]] doctor at Lavender Hill.  After having dinner with his sister, Duncan works at the candle factory.  It is implied that the boss adores him, and he shies away when a younger co-worker brags about his latest indiscretion and invites Duncan to join him.   \nWhen he leaves work, Duncan is surprised to see Fraser waiting for him at the gates.  He invites Duncan to a pub by the water, and Duncan reluctantly agrees, mainly because he doesn't want Mr Mundy to worry.  \n\nFraser makes several calls at Duncan's for dinner.  One night, however, he doesn't show up, and Duncan is quite upset, while Mr Mundy is relieved.\n\n===1944===\n'''Duncan'''\n\nDuncan has been imprisoned in [[HM Prison Wormwood Scrubs|Wormwood Scrubs]] for three years now, and Viv and her father visit him once a month.  Duncan's time is juxtaposed between prison guard Mr Mundy's kind and defeatist demeanour and Fraser's free-thinking, free-acting attitude.\n  \n'''Viv '''\n\nViv is working as a typist, along with many other girls, and lodges at a boarding house with some of her co-workers.  She meets Reggie, who is married, at anonymous hotels once every five weeks, whenever Reggie is permitted leave from Wales.  \n\n'''Kay'''\n\nKay works as an emergency response ambulance worker along with Mickey.  She spends long nights cleaning up after air raids.\n\nOne night a call comes in to an air raid that has occurred on her street.  She assumes Helen's been asleep throughout the entire raid and panics.  She runs to the rubble to where her flat used to be and weeps at her loss.\n  \n'''Helen'''\n\nHelen works for the government in a division that assists those who've lost their belongings in the war.  By chance she runs into Julia, a woman who was once acquainted with Kay.  \nOne night Helen is unable to sleep and leaves for Julia's flat.  They take a walk around the ruins, and when another air raid alarm is sounded, they run amongst more ruins and hide from the chaos.\n\n===1941===\n\nViv is on a crowded train, filled with civilians and military men.  By chance, she meets a soldier named Reggie.  They engage in a conversation under awkward circumstances, and he reveals to her that he is stuck in an unhappy marriage.\n\n\nKay is responding to an emergency call along with Mickey.  They arrive at the scene and find one woman dead, another young woman caught underneath rubble, and two others trapped behind more debris.\n\n==Awards==\n* Man Booker Prize for Fiction (shortlist), 2006\n* Orange Prize for Fiction (shortlist), 2006\n* Lambda Literary Award for Lesbian Fiction, 2007\n\n==TV-movie adaptation==\nOn 25 November 2010, BBC2 network announced the cast for the 90-minute television adaptation of ''The Night Watch.''<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/11_november/25/night.shtml BBC press release]</ref> It was adapted by [[Paula Milne]] and directed by Richard Laxton and was broadcast on 12 July 2011 on BBC Two.\n\nCast:<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b012mb0r Programme page on BBC Online]</ref>\n\n* [[Anna Maxwell Martin]] as Kay\n* [[Claire Foy]] as Helen\n* [[Jodie Whittaker]] as Viv\n* [[Harry Treadaway]] as Duncan\n* [[Anna Wilson-Jones]] as Julia\n* [[JJ Feild]] as Robert\n* [[Liam Garrigan]] as Reggie\n* [[Claudie Blakley]] as Nancy\n* [[Kenneth Cranham]] as Mr Mundy\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sarahwaters.com/books/the-night-watch/ Book description at Sarah Waters' official webpage]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jan/08/fiction.sarahwaters Smoother than velvet:] Book review at The Guardian\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/26/books/review/26leavitt.html?ex=1175659200&en=724d48edfc187f77&ei=5070 This Is London:] Book review at the New York Times\n*[http://nishitak.com/2017/09/30/night-watch/ Great book on London during the Blitz] Book review at Nishita's Rants and Raves\n{{Sarah Waters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Night Watch, The}}\n[[Category:Historical novels]]\n[[Category:World War II novels]]\n[[Category:2006 British novels]]\n[[Category:English novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Sarah Waters]]\n[[Category:Novels set in London]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1941]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1944]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the 1940s]]\n[[Category:British novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:2000s LGBT novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2006 historical fiction novel}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The Night Watch\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = TheNightWatchcover2006.jpg\n| caption       = UK first edition cover\n| author        = [[Sarah Waters]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  = TWBG - Duncan Spilling<br>Lettering: Stephen Raw\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Historical fiction]]\n| publisher     = Virago\n| release_date  = 2 Feb 2006 (UK)\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages         = 480 pp\n| isbn          = 1-84408-246-6\n| oclc= 62265716\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''The Night Watch''''' is a dark, 2006 [[historical fiction]] novel by  [[Sarah Waters]]. It was shortlisted for both the 2006 [[Man Booker Prize]] and the 2006 [[Orange Prize]]. The novel, which is told backward through third-person narrative, takes place in 1940s London during and after [[World War II]]. The storyline follows the fragmented lives and the strange interconnections between Kay, Helen and Julia, three lesbians; Viv, a straight woman; and Duncan, her brother, whose sexuality is ambiguous. The war, with its never-ending night watches, serves as a horrifying context, backdrop and metaphor as a constant reminder of the morbidity that surrounds life and love.\n\n==Plot summary==\n{{Plot|date=November 2008}}\n\n===1947===\n'''Kay'''\n\nThe novel begins with Kay Langrish-a woman broken by the war. She spends her days locked in her room in London, watching her landlord's patients arrive and leave at precisely the same hours every day.   The only human contact that Kay is seen to be having at this stage in the narrative is with another lesbian, Mickey.  Kay is suggested to be wealthy by her residence in [[Lavender Hill]].  One night, while waiting for the cinema doors to open, Viv, a woman from her past appears and hands to her a gold ring.  \n\n'''Helen'''\n\nHelen and her assistant Viv run a match-making agency near [[Bond Street]] for individuals who have either lost their loved one or were disappointed to see how much their sweethearts had changed after the war.  The work itself is not very fulfilling, but their hesitant friendship keeps them entertained.\n\n'''Viv'''\n\nAfter work, Viv sets off to meet her brother Duncan, who lives with a much older gentleman named Mr Mundy.  The three of them meet on a weekly basis for dinner at Mr Mundy's, and Viv always brings a tin of meat for them to share.   Duncan shrugs off news of their father, and proceeds to show Viv the latest addition to his antiques collection.  Viv politely ends the night and heads for the railway station, but she doesn't go home to her father's.  \n\nOn the same day that Helen wanted to confide her love for Julia to Viv, the two women receive an unexpected visit from Robert Fraser, Duncan\u2019s old cellmate.  He asks to speak with her regarding Duncan, and his present condition: collecting antiques (which Robert finds morbid), living with Mr Mundy, whom both men knew at the prison, and working at a candle factory.  Viv dismisses Fraser, feeling as though he thinks she and her father haven\u2019t done enough to help Duncan\u2019s situation and explains that he simply doesn\u2019t know everything.\n  \n'''Duncan'''\n\nDuncan accompanies Mr Mundy, or \"Uncle Horace,\" as he referred to him in public, every Tuesday to his [[Christian Science]] doctor at Lavender Hill.  After having dinner with his sister, Duncan works at the candle factory.  It is implied that the boss adores him, and he shies away when a younger co-worker brags about his latest indiscretion and invites Duncan to join him.   \nWhen he leaves work, Duncan is surprised to see Fraser waiting for him at the gates.  He invites Duncan to a pub by the water, and Duncan reluctantly agrees, mainly because he doesn't want Mr Mundy to worry.  \n\nFraser makes several calls at Duncan's for dinner.  One night, however, he doesn't show up, and Duncan is quite upset, while Mr Mundy is relieved.\n\n===1944===\n'''Duncan'''\n\nDuncan has been imprisoned in [[HM Prison Wormwood Scrubs|Wormwood Scrubs]] for three years now, and Viv and her father visit him once a month.  Duncan's time is juxtaposed between prison guard Mr Mundy's kind and defeatist demeanour and Fraser's free-thinking, free-acting attitude.\n  \n'''Viv '''\n\nViv is working as a typist, along with many other girls, and lodges at a boarding house with some of her co-workers.  She meets Reggie, who is married, at anonymous hotels once every five weeks, whenever Reggie is permitted leave from Wales.  \n\n'''Kay'''\n\nKay works as an emergency response ambulance worker along with Mickey.  She spends long nights cleaning up after air raids.\n\nOne night a call comes in to an air raid that has occurred on her street.  She assumes Helen's been asleep throughout the entire raid and panics.  She runs to the rubble to where her flat used to be and weeps at her loss.\n  \n'''Helen'''\n\nHelen works for the government in a division that assists those who've lost their belongings in the war.  By chance she runs into Julia, a woman who was once acquainted with Kay.  \nOne night Helen is unable to sleep and leaves for Julia's flat.  They take a walk around the ruins, and when another air raid alarm is sounded, they run amongst more ruins and hide from the chaos.\n\n===1941===\n\nViv is on a crowded train, filled with civilians and military men.  By chance, she meets a soldier named Reggie.  They engage in a conversation under awkward circumstances, and he reveals to her that he is stuck in an unhappy marriage.\n\n\nKay is responding to an emergency call along with Mickey.  They arrive at the scene and find one woman dead, another young woman caught underneath rubble, and two others trapped behind more debris.\n\n==Awards==\n* Man Booker Prize for Fiction (shortlist), 2006\n* Orange Prize for Fiction (shortlist), 2006\n* Lambda Literary Award for Lesbian Fiction, 2007\n\n==TV-movie adaptation==\nOn 25 November 2010, BBC2 network announced the cast for the 90-minute television adaptation of ''The Night Watch.''<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/11_november/25/night.shtml BBC press release]</ref> It was adapted by [[Paula Milne]] and directed by Richard Laxton and was broadcast on 12 July 2011 on BBC Two.\n\nCast:<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b012mb0r Programme page on BBC Online]</ref>\n\n* [[Anna Maxwell Martin]] as Kay\n* [[Claire Foy]] as Helen\n* [[Jodie Whittaker]] as Viv\n* [[Harry Treadaway]] as Duncan\n* [[Anna Wilson-Jones]] as Julia\n* [[JJ Feild]] as Robert\n* [[Liam Garrigan]] as Reggie\n* [[Claudie Blakley]] as Nancy\n* [[Kenneth Cranham]] as Mr Mundy\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sarahwaters.com/books/the-night-watch/ Book description at Sarah Waters' official webpage]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jan/08/fiction.sarahwaters Smoother than velvet:] Book review at The Guardian\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/26/books/review/26leavitt.html?ex=1175659200&en=724d48edfc187f77&ei=5070 This Is London:] Book review at the New York Times\n*[http://nishitak.com/2017/09/30/night-watch/ Great book on London during the Blitz] Book review at Nishita's Rants and Raves\n{{Sarah Waters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Night Watch, The}}\n[[Category:Historical novels]]\n[[Category:World War II novels]]\n[[Category:2006 British novels]]\n[[Category:English novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Sarah Waters]]\n[[Category:Novels set in London]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1941]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1944]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the 1940s]]\n[[Category:British novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:2000s LGBT novels]]\n", "name_user": "Sfjohna", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Night_Watch_(Waters_novel)"}
{"title_page": "Danny Nedelko", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Danny Nedelko\n| cover      = Idles - Danny Nedelko.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Idles (band)|Idles]]\n| album      = [[Joy as an Act of Resistance]]\n| released   = 5 June 2018\n| format     =\n* [[Single (music)|7-inch]]\n* [[Music download|digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   = August\u2013October 2017\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n*[[Punk rock]]\n| length     = 3:24\n| label      = [[Partisan Records|Partisan]]\n| writer     = Idles\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Colossus (Idles song)|Colossus]]\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = [[Samaritans (song)|Samaritans]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|QkF_G-RF66M|\"Danny Nedelko\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Danny Nedelko'''\" is a song by British [[punk rock]] band [[Idles (band)|Idles]]. The track was the second single from their second studio album, ''[[Joy as an Act of Resistance]]''. The track was released as a single on 5 June 2018.\n\nConsidered a pro-immigration track, the track has been described a hybrid of the British pub rock and classic hardcore punk sound, with a modern retrofitting on the [[European migrant crisis]] of the 2010s.\n\n== Composition ==\nThe track is the story of Ukrainian immigrant, Danny Nedelko, who is a close friend of the members of the band <ref>{{cite web |last1=Lyle |first1=Gina |title=Idles Announces New Album Joy As An Act of Resistance for August 2018 Release and Affirmation of Immigrants in New Video for \u201cDanny Nedelko\u201d |url=https://music.mxdwn.com/2018/06/06/news/idles-announces-new-album-joy-as-an-act-of-resistance-for-august-2018-release-and-affirmation-of-immigrants-in-new-video-for-danny-nedelko/ |website=Mxdwn.com |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=6 June 2018}}</ref> and the lead singer of the band [[Heavy Lungs]]. The song's lyrics take aim at and are heavily critical of [[nationalism]],<ref name=\"stereogum\">{{cite web |last1=DeVille |first1=Chris |title=IDLES \u2013 \"Danny Nedelko\" Video |url=https://www.stereogum.com/1999926/idles-danny-nedelko-video/video/ |website=[[Stereogum]] |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=5 June 2018}}</ref> while making the focus of the song as a celebration of multiculturalism and diversity.<ref name=\"hakimian\">{{cite web |last1=Hakimian |first1=Rob |title=Track Of The Day: IDLES pen a stomping ode to their immigrant pals 'Danny Nedelko', announce second album |url=https://www.thefourohfive.com/music/article/track-of-the-day-idles-pen-a-stomping-ode-to-their-immigrant-pals-danny-nedelko-announce-second-album-152 |website=The 405 |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=5 June 2018}}</ref> The song celebrates various immigrants from [[Freddie Mercury]] to the \"local Polish butcher\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pountain |first1=David |title='Danny Nedelko'  by Idles is a pro-immigrant punk anthem |url=https://guestlist.net/article/93311/danny-nedelko-by-idles-is-a-pro-immigration-punk-anthem |website=Guestlist |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nChris DeVille, writing for ''[[Stereogum]]'' described the track as \"a bit of righteous post-punk agitprop that morphs into something like a soccer chant along the way, is a tribute to the immigrants that have taken so much heat from nationalists across Europe and America lately\".<ref name=\"stereogum\"/> ''Born Music'' compared the track to contemporary bands such as, [[Metz (band)|METZ]], [[Savages (band)|Savages]], and [[Protomartyr (band)|Protomartyr]]. The website also stated that despite \"the trademark growls from Joe Talbot are there, and the bouts of guitar feedback and angular riffage are present, this is a much more uplifting song\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Idles Pen the Pro-immigrant Anthem \u2018Danny Nedelko\u2019 |url=http://www.bornmusiconline.com/podcast/idles-pen-the-pro-immigrant-anthem-danny-nedelko/ |website=Born Music |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=7 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nThe song's message, and music video has been well-received by contemporary music critics. Chris DeVille, writing for ''[[Stereogum]]'' said of the song, \"Nedelko is a total ham, and his charisma carries the concept to success\".<ref name=\"stereogum\"/> Rob Hakimian, writing for ''[[The 405 (website)|The 405]]'' praised the lyricism and musicianship, calling \"Danny Nedelko\" \"a rollicking torrent of guitars and chant-along lyricism. This is sure to become a live anthem that will galvanise fans all over the world.\"<ref name=\"hakimian\"/>\n\nJennifer Buchanan, writing for ''Indie Shuffle'' described the song as \"pure punk rock\". \"On \u201cDanny Nedelko,\u201d Idles shred guitar riffs over lyrics that address the current anti-immigration movement. It is a true song for the people. \u201cDanny Nedelko\u201d is downright catchy while maintaining Idles\u2019 politically charged roots. The chanting chorus is unapologetically British and reminiscent of [[Buzzcocks]]. If there is a [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] football player whose name rhymes with \u201cDanny Nedelko\u201d he should expect to have this sung at him this season\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Buchanan |first1=Jennifer |title=Idles - Danny Nedelko |url=https://www.indieshuffle.com/idles-danny-nedelko/ |website=indieshuffle.com |accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nJamie MacMillan, writing for ''[[Dork (magazine)|Dork]]'' magazine raved the song's message, composition, and believed the track was important in the wake of the migrant crisis. Of the track, MacMillan said that \"once again, IDLES show themselves to be a band willing to tackle the important subjects and turn it into moshpit gold. We\u2019ve never needed them more.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=MacMillan |first1=Jamie |title=IDLES - Danny Nedelko: Once again, IDLES show themselves to be a band willing to tackle the important subjects and turn it into moshpit gold. |url=https://www.readdork.com/bangers/idles-danny-nedelko |website=Dork |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Live performances ==\n\"Danny Nedelko\" made its television appearance on ''[[Later... with Jools Holland]]'' on 25 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yeung |first1=Vivian |title=IDLES perform pro-immigration anthem Danny Nedelko on Later\u2026 with Jools Holland |url=https://crackmagazine.net/2018/09/idles-perform-pro-immigration-anthem-danny-nedelko-on-later-with-jools-holland/ |website=[[Crack Magazine|Crack]] |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=26 September 2018}}</ref> The performance of \"Nedelko\" on Jools Holland was described by [[DIY (magazine)|''DIY'']] magazine as a chaotic and triumphant rendering of the song.<ref>{{cite web |title=Idles bring chaotic, triumphant version of 'Danny Nedelko' to Jools Holland |url=http://diymag.com/2018/09/26/idles-danny-nedelko-jools-holland-watch |website=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Music video ==\nThe music video was directed by the members of Idles. It features Danny Nedelko himself, who spends part of the time parodying [[Bob Dylan]]'s \"[[Subterranean Homesick Blues]]\". Nedelko is wearing a T-shirt that reads, \"no one is an island\". Throughout the video, Nedelko is posing for photos with immigrants to the United Kingdom, while posting with the \"OK\" hand gesture as an attempt to reclaim the gesture back from white nationalists.<ref name=\"stereogum\"/>\n\nAlex Gallacher, writing for [[Folk Radio UK]] described the video for Nedelko as \"an uplifting and unifying video\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gallacher |first1=Alex |title=Idles Announce Joy as an Act of Resistance and Share Video for Pro-immigration Anthem \"Danny Nedelko\" |url=https://www.folkradio.co.uk/2018/06/watch-idles-danny-nedelko/ |website=[[Folk Radio UK]] |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs release|12317810|Danny Nedelko|type=single}}\n\n{{Idles}}\n\n[[Category:2018 singles]]\n[[Category:2018 songs]]\n[[Category:Idles (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Partisan Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs against racism and xenophobia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Danny Nedelko\n| cover      = Idles - Danny Nedelko.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Idles (band)|Idles]]\n| album      = [[Joy as an Act of Resistance]]\n| released   = 5 June 2018\n| format     =\n* [[Single (music)|7-inch]]\n* [[Music download|digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   = August\u2013October 2017\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n*[[Punk rock]]\n| length     = 3:24\n| label      = [[Partisan Records|Partisan]]\n| writer     = Idles\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Colossus (Idles song)|Colossus]]\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = [[Samaritans (song)|Samaritans]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|QkF_G-RF66M|\"Danny Nedelko\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Danny Nedelko'''\" is a song by British [[punk rock]] band [[Idles (band)|Idles]]. The track was the second single from their second studio album, ''[[Joy as an Act of Resistance]]''. The track was released as a single on 5 June 2018.\n\nConsidered a pro-immigration track, the track has been described a hybrid of the British pub rock and classic hardcore punk sound, with a modern retrofitting on the [[European migrant crisis]] of the 2010s.\n\n== Composition ==\nThe track is the story of Ukrainian immigrant, Danny Nedelko, who is a close friend of the members of the band <ref>{{cite web |last1=Lyle |first1=Gina |title=Idles Announces New Album Joy As An Act of Resistance for August 2018 Release and Affirmation of Immigrants in New Video for \u201cDanny Nedelko\u201d |url=https://music.mxdwn.com/2018/06/06/news/idles-announces-new-album-joy-as-an-act-of-resistance-for-august-2018-release-and-affirmation-of-immigrants-in-new-video-for-danny-nedelko/ |website=Mxdwn.com |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=6 June 2018}}</ref> and the lead singer of the band [[Heavy Lungs]]. The songs lyrics take aim at and are heavily critical of [[nationalism]],<ref name=\"stereogum\">{{cite web |last1=DeVille |first1=Chris |title=IDLES \u2013 \u201cDanny Nedelko\u201d Video |url=https://www.stereogum.com/1999926/idles-danny-nedelko-video/video/ |website=[[Stereogum]] |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=5 June 2018}}</ref> while making the focus of the song as a celebration of multiculturalism and diversity.<ref name=\"hakimian\">{{cite web |last1=Hakimian |first1=Rob |title=Track Of The Day: IDLES pen a stomping ode to their immigrant pals 'Danny Nedelko', announce second album |url=https://www.thefourohfive.com/music/article/track-of-the-day-idles-pen-a-stomping-ode-to-their-immigrant-pals-danny-nedelko-announce-second-album-152 |website=The 405 |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=5 June 2018}}</ref> The song celebrates various immigrants from [[Freddie Mercury]] to the \"local Polish butcher\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pountain |first1=David |title='Danny Nedelko'  by Idles is a pro-immigrant punk anthem |url=https://guestlist.net/article/93311/danny-nedelko-by-idles-is-a-pro-immigration-punk-anthem |website=Guestlist |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nChris DeVille, writing for ''[[Stereogum]]'' described the track as \"a bit of righteous post-punk agitprop that morphs into something like a soccer chant along the way, is a tribute to the immigrants that have taken so much heat from nationalists across Europe and America lately\".<ref name=\"stereogum\"/> ''Born Music'' compared the track to contemporary bands such as, [[Metz (band)|METZ]], [[Savages (band)|Savages]], and [[Protomartyr (band)|Protomartyr]]. The website also stated that despite \"the trademark growls from Joe Talbot are there, and the bouts of guitar feedback and angular riffage are present, this is a much more uplifting song\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Idles Pen the Pro-immigrant Anthem \u2018Danny Nedelko\u2019 |url=http://www.bornmusiconline.com/podcast/idles-pen-the-pro-immigrant-anthem-danny-nedelko/ |website=Born Music |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=7 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nThe song's message, and music video has been well-received by contemporary music critics. Chris DeVille, writing for ''[[Stereogum]]'' said of the song, \"Nedelko is a total ham, and his charisma carries the concept to success\".<ref name=\"stereogum\"/> Rob Hakimian, writing for ''[[The 405 (website)|The 405]]'' praised the lyricism and musicianship, calling \"Danny Nedelko\" \"a rollicking torrent of guitars and chant-along lyricism. This is sure to become a live anthem that will galvanise fans all over the world.\"<ref name=\"hakimian\"/>\n\nJennifer Buchanan, writing for ''Indie Shuffle'' described the song as \"pure punk rock\". \"On \u201cDanny Nedelko,\u201d Idles shred guitar riffs over lyrics that address the current anti-immigration movement. It is a true song for the people. \u201cDanny Nedelko\u201d is downright catchy while maintaining Idles\u2019 politically charged roots. The chanting chorus is unapologetically British and reminiscent of [[Buzzcocks]]. If there is a [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] football player whose name rhymes with \u201cDanny Nedelko\u201d he should expect to have this sung at him this season\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Buchanan |first1=Jennifer |title=Idles - Danny Nedelko |url=https://www.indieshuffle.com/idles-danny-nedelko/ |website=indieshuffle.com |accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nJamie MacMillan, writing for ''[[Dork (magazine)|Dork]]'' magazine raved the song's message, composition, and believed the track was important in the wake of the migrant crisis. Of the track, MacMillan said that \"once again, IDLES show themselves to be a band willing to tackle the important subjects and turn it into moshpit gold. We\u2019ve never needed them more.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=MacMillan |first1=Jamie |title=IDLES - Danny Nedelko: Once again, IDLES show themselves to be a band willing to tackle the important subjects and turn it into moshpit gold. |url=https://www.readdork.com/bangers/idles-danny-nedelko |website=Dork |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Live performances ==\n\"Danny Nedelko\" made its television appearance on ''[[Later... with Jools Holland]]'' on 25 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yeung |first1=Vivian |title=IDLES perform pro-immigration anthem Danny Nedelko on Later\u2026 with Jools Holland |url=https://crackmagazine.net/2018/09/idles-perform-pro-immigration-anthem-danny-nedelko-on-later-with-jools-holland/ |website=[[Crack Magazine|Crack]] |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=26 September 2018}}</ref> The performance of \"Nedelko\" on Jools Holland was described by [[DIY (magazine)|''DIY'']] magazine as a chaotic and triumphant rendering of the song.<ref>{{cite web |title=Idles bring chaotic, triumphant version of 'Danny Nedelko' to Jools Holland |url=http://diymag.com/2018/09/26/idles-danny-nedelko-jools-holland-watch |website=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Music video ==\nThe music video was directed by the members of Idles. It features Danny Nedelko himself, who spends part of the time parodying [[Bob Dylan]]'s \"[[Subterranean Homesick Blues]]\". Nedelko is wearing a T-shirt that reads, \"no one is an island\". Throughout the video, Nedelko is posing for photos with immigrants to the United Kingdom, while posting with the \"OK\" hand gesture as an attempt to reclaim the gesture back from white nationalists.<ref name=\"stereogum\"/> \n\nAlex Gallacher, writing for [[Folk Radio UK]] described the video for Nedelko as \"an uplifting and unifying video\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gallacher |first1=Alex |title=Idles Announce Joy as an Act of Resistance and Share Video for Pro-immigration Anthem \u201cDanny Nedelko\u201d |url=https://www.folkradio.co.uk/2018/06/watch-idles-danny-nedelko/ |website=[[Folk Radio UK]] |accessdate=14 October 2018 |date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs release|12317810|Danny Nedelko|type=single}}\n\n{{Idles}}\n\n[[Category:2018 singles]]\n[[Category:2018 songs]]\n[[Category:Idles (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Partisan Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs against racism and xenophobia]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: songs lyrics \u2192 song's lyrics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danny_Nedelko"}
{"title_page": "Frances Halsband", "text_new": "{{short description|American architect}}\n[[File:FrancesHalsband-square.jpg|thumb]]\n'''Frances Halsband''' FAIA (born October 30, 1943, in [[New York City]]) is an American architect and educator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arch.umd.edu/arch/kea-recipient/frances-halsband|title=Frances Halsband:  Kea Distinguished Professor in the Architecture program University of Maryland|last=|first=|date=Spring 2009|website=University of Maryland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> She is a founder, with Robert Kliment, of [[Kliment Halsband Architects]], a New York City design firm widely recognized for preservation, adaptive reuse and master planning projects.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Woods|first=Lynn|url=https://hudsonvalleyone.com/2015/01/23/pioneering-architect-frances-halsband-got-her-start-on-woodstocks-village-green/|title=Pioneering architect Frances Halsband got her start on Woodstock\u2019s Village Green|date=23 January 2015|work=Hudson Valley One|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Significant works include The [[Brown University]] Framework for Physical Planning,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brown.edu/web/pae/documents/Institutional_Master_Plan_2006.pdf|title=Brown Master Plan Kliment Halsband Architects|last=|first=|date=30 March 2006|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> [[Long Island Rail Road|Long Island Railroad]] Entrance at 34 Street,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/01/08/realestate/postings-for-the-dashing-commuter-lirr-finishing-34th-st-pavilion.html|title=POSTINGS: For the Dashing Commuter|date=8 January 1995|work=The New York Times|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Visitor Center at [[Franklin D. Roosevelt Presidential Library and Museum|Franklin Roosevelt Presidential Library]],<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Hutton|first=Ann|url=https://hudsonvalleyone.com/2015/05/22/fdrs-hyde-park-hive-on-the-hudson/|title=FDRs Hyde Park Hive on the Hudson|date=22 May 2015|work=Hudson Valley One|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mount Sinai Health System|Mount Sinai]] Ambulatory Surgery Facility Kyabirwa Uganda.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Pintos|first=Paula|url=https://www.archdaily.com/928402/mount-sinai-kyabirwa-surgical-facility-kliment-halsband-architects|title=Mount Sinai Kyabirwa Surgical Facility Kliment Halsband Architects|date=December 2019|work=ArchDaily|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aiany.org/architecture/awards/2020-aiany-design-awards/|title=AIANY 2020 Design Awards Winners|last=|first=|date=January 2020|website=AIANY|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|last=Crosbie|first=Michael J|url=https://commonedge.org/new-york-architects-kliment-halsband-design-a-surgery-clinic-in-kyabirwa-uganda/|title=New York Architects Kliment Halsband Design A Surgery Clinic in Kyabirwa Uganda|date=25 November 2019|work=CommonEdge|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The firm received the AIA Firm Award in 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Architecture_Firm_Award&oldid=915263936|title=Architecture Firm Award Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=Wikipedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> and the New York AIA Medal of Honor in 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aia.org/awards/7276-architecture-firm-award|title=Architecture Firm Award|last=|first=|date=|website=AIANY|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1991 to 1994 Halsband was dean of the [[Pratt Institute School of Architecture|School of Architecture]] at [[Pratt Institute]],<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/08/15/arts/architecture-dean-named.html|title=Architecture Dean Named|date=15 August 1991|work=The New York Times|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|last=Wiseman|first=Carter|url=https://nymag.com/|title=A Dean of the Real|date=2 December 1991|work=New York Magazine|access-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and she has taught at [[Harvard University]],  [[Columbia University]], [[Rice University School of Architecture|Rice University]], [[University of Pennsylvania]], [[University of California, Berkeley]] and other institutions.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://commons.pratt.edu/mistressesofarchitecture/frances-halsband/|title=Pratt Mistresses of Architecture: Frances Halsband|last=|first=|date=March 2020|website=Pratt Mistresses of Pratt|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> She was the first woman president of [[American Institute of Architects|AIA New York]]<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://calendar.aiany.org/2018/11/05/leadership-breakfast-with-frances-halsband-faia/|title=Leadership Breakfast with Frances Halsband|last=|first=|date=8 February 2019|website=AIANY Calendar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> and The Architectural League of New York.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|last=Gamolina|first=Julia|url=https://www.madamearchitect.org/interviews/2020/3/11/frances-halsband|title=Power to Move Forward: Frances Halsband on Giving Back, Staying in Touch, and Ethical Behavior|date=11 March 2020|work=Madame Architect|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She is a former commissioner of the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|New York City Landmarks Commission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dna.bwaf.org/architect/halsband-frances|title=Beverly Willis Architecture Foundation: Frances Halsband|last=|first=|date=|website=Beverly Willis Architecture Foundation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|last=Hoechstetter|first=Marissa|url=https://msmagazine.com/2018/11/02/fellowship-leadership-fighting-sexual-harassment-architecture/|title=Fellowship is Leadership: Fighting Sexual Harassment in Architecture|date=2 November 2018|work=Ms. Magazine|access-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018 Halsband lead a successful effort to amend the AIA Code of Ethics<ref name=\":13\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aia.org/pages/3296-code-of-ethics-and-professional-conduct|title=AIA Code of Ethics|last=|first=|date=|website=AIA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> to prohibit harassment or discrimination and commit to fostering a professional environment of mutual respect and equity.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Post|first=Nadine M|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/46169-lighting-a-fire-under-the-aia-in-a-crusade-against-all-types-of-workplace-abuse|title=Lighting a Fire Under the AIA in a Crusade Against All Types of Workplace Abuse|date=10 January 2019|work=Engineering News Record|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Budds|first=Diana|url=https://www.curbed.com/2019/8/5/20699746/architecture-sexual-harrassment-aia-ethics-code|title=Inside the AIA\u2019s efforts to address #MeToo|date=5 August 2019|work=Curbed|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  In recognition of this effort she was named one of [[Engineering News-Record]] (ENR) Top 25 Newsmakers.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2019 she received an Honorary Doctor of Design from the [[NewSchool of Architecture and Design|NewSchool of Architecture San Diego]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://network.aia.org/cof/home/executivecommittee|title=Network AIA: Executive Committee|last=|first=|date=|website=Network AIA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life & Education ==\nShe received her B.A. at [[Swarthmore College]] in 1965 and a Master's from [[Columbia University]] in 1968.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www2.arch.uiuc.edu/organizations/wia/disprofs/halsbandfrances.html |title=\"Women in Architecture\" at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign |access-date=2008-06-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829000641/http://www2.arch.uiuc.edu/organizations/wia/disprofs/halsbandfrances.html |archive-date=2008-08-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>Lorenz, Clare, Women in Architecture: a contemporary perspective,  Rizzoli,  New York,  1990 p. 44</ref>  She has served on juries for design awards, chaired the 1999 [[American Institute of Architects]] Committee on Design, and served as [[Center for Architecture|AIA New York's]] first woman president in 1991.<ref>[http://www.aia.org/aiarchitect/thisweek07/0202/0202dp.cfm AIA Profile]</ref><ref>https://www.aiany.org/news/aiany-supported-resolution-leads-to-important-changes-to-aia-code-of-ethics/</ref> Halsband and Kliment were married in 1971 in Woodstock New York.\u00a0Their son, Alexander Halsband Kliment was born in 1979. They made their home in New York City and Woodstock New York.<ref name=\":0\" /> Kliment retired from KHA in 2013, and passed away in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Martin|first=Olivia|url=https://archpaper.com/2017/06/robert-kliment-cofounder-kliment-halsband/|title=Robert Kliment, cofounder of Kliment Halsband Architects, has passed|date=9 January 2017|work=The Architect's Newspaper|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Professional Practice ==\n\n*[[Kliment Halsband Architects]], New York, NY - 2008-Present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kliment-halsband.com/studio-history/|title=Studio History|last=|first=|date=|website=Kliment Halsband Architects|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n* R.M.Kliment & Frances Halsband Architects, New York, NY - 1978-2008\n* R.M.Kliment Architect, New York, NY - 1972-1977\n*[[Mitchell/Giurgola|Mitchell/Giurgola Architects]], New York, NY -1968-1972<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Selected Projects ===\n''This selection is specific to projects for which Halsband has been principally responsible''\n\n* [[Arcadia University, Pennsylvania|Arcadia University]] Commons, Glenside, PA (2012)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cropper|first=Purnell|url=https://www.arcadia.edu/news/2010/04/architect-includes-geothermal-wells-walking-bridge-commons-design|title=Architect Includes Geothermal Wells, Walking Bridge in Commons Design|date=23 April 2010|work=Arcadia University News|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Arcadia University, Pennsylvania|Arcadia University]] Landman Library, Glenside, PA (2003)<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first= |url=http://info.aia.org/aiarchitect/thisweek05/tw0401/0401libraryawards.htm|title=Eight Beautiful Buildings Win 2005 Library Awards|date=April 2005|work=AIArchitects|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Avalon Morningside Park|Avalon Morningside]] at the [[Cathedral of St. John the Divine]], New York, NY (2008)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Horsley|first=Carter|url=https://www.cityrealty.com/nyc/morningside-heights/avalon-morningside-park-1-morningside-drive/review/44851|title=Avalon Morningside Park, 1 Morningside Drive|date=|work=City Realty|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Brown University]] Strategic Framework for Physical Planning, Providence, RI (2003/2009)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Dartmouth College]] Roth Center for Jewish Life, Hanover, NH (1998)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Slating|first=Peter|date=September 1993|title=SCOOP|url=https://usmodernist.org/AIANY/AIANY-1993-09.pdf|journal=Oculus|volume=56|pages=3|via=US Modernist}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rtmudge.com/awards/|title=Architecture Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=Randall T Mudge and Associates|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Friends Seminary]], New York, NY (2019)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pintos|first=Paula|url=https://www.archdaily.com/935714/friends-seminary-school-kliment-halsband-architects?ad_source=search&ad_medium=search_result_all|title=Friends Seminary / Kliment Halsband Architects|date=March 2020|work=ArchDaily|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Lentz|first=Linda C|url=https://www.architecturalrecord.com/articles/14450-friends-seminary-by-kliment-halsband-architects|title=Friends Seminary by Kliment Halsband Architects|date=February 2020|work=Architectural Record|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Johns Hopkins University]] Gilman Hall, Baltimore, MD (2010)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seward|first=Aaron|url=https://archpaper.com/2010/10/gilman-hall-at-johns-hopkins-university/|title=Gilman Hall at Johns Hopkins University|date=27 October 2010|work=The Architect's Newspaper|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Long Island Rail Road|Long Island Railroad]] Entrance at [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Pennsylvania Station]], New York, NY (1994)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Mount Sinai Health System|Mount Sinai]] Ambulatory Surgery Facility Kyabirwa Uganda, Africa (2019)<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" />\n* [[University of Chicago]] Neubauer Collegium for Culture and Society, Chicago, IL (2015)<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.aiachicago.org/dea_archive/2015/university-of-chicago-neubauer-collegium-for-culture-and-society1/|title=University of Chicago Neubauer Collegium|date=2015|work=AIA Chicago|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] South College, Amherst, MA (2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umass.edu/cp/south-college|title=South College|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Massachusetts Amherst|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Franklin D. Roosevelt Presidential Library and Museum|Franklin D. Roosevelt Presidential Library]] Henry A. Wallace Visitor and Education Center, Hyde Park, NY (2004)<ref name=\":4\" />\n* [[Zen Mountain Monastery]] Sangha House, Mt. Tremper, NY (2013)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halsband|first=Frances|date=|title=A Different Kind of Place|url=https://faithandform.com/feature/a-different-kind-of-place/|journal=Faith and Form|volume=52|pages=|via=www.faithandform.com}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Achievements ==\n\n=== Honors ===\n\n* Honorary Doctor of Design, [[NewSchool of Architecture and Design]] - 2019<ref name=\":11\" />\n* [[Engineering News-Record|Engineering News Record]] 2018 Top 25 Newsmaker - 2019<ref name=\":1\" />\n* AIA Firm Award, R.M.Kliment & Frances Halsband Architects - 1998<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Architecture_Firm_Award&oldid=915263936|title=Architecture Firm Award|last=|first=|date=|website=Wikipedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n* AIA New York Medal of Honor, R.M.Kliment & Frances Halsband Architects - 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://46u0j30o449zq8181dfurbcj-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/AIA-New-York-Chapter-Awards-History-as-of-10_2017.pdf|title=R.M. Kliment & Frances Halsband Architects|last=|first=|date=|website=AIA New York Chapter Awards History|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aiany.org/membership/join/chapter-recognition/|title=Chapter Recognition|last=|first=|date=|website=AIANY|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Fellow of the American Institute of Architects]] - 1986\n\n=== Civic & Professional Boards ===\n\n* AIA [https://www.aia.org/pages/6075263-college-of-fellows College of Fellows] Executive Committee - 2019-Present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aia.org/pages/6075263-college-of-fellows|title=College of Fellows Leadership|last=Halsband|first=Frances|date=|website=American Institute of Architects|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Castellana|first=John|date=13 August 2019|title=Welcome Frances Halsband, FAIA!|url=https://issuu.com/aiacollegeoffellows/docs/cof_newsletter_august_2019_draft|journal=The AIA College of Fellows Newsletter|volume=|pages=17|via=ISSUU}}</ref>\n* [[Harvard University]], Design Review Panel - 2005-2009<ref name=\":9\" />\n* [[Byrdcliffe Colony|Woodstock Byrdcliffe Guild]], Board of Directors, (President 2008-2013) - 2003-Present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.woodstockguild.org/about-byrdcliffe/|title=About Byrdcliffe|last=|first=|date=|website=Woodstock Guild|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Brown University|Brown University,]] Architect Advisor, Board of Trustees - 2002-2013<ref>{{Cite news|last=Boucher|first=Norman|url=https://www.brownalumnimagazine.com/articles/2007-06-15/blocking-out-the-future|title=Blocking Out The Future|date=June 2004|work=Brown Alumni Magazine|access-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* AIA Committee on Design, Chair 1999<ref>{{Cite news|last=Livingston|first=Heather|url=http://info.aia.org/aiarchitect/thisweek07/0202/0202dp.htm|title=Face of the AIA: Frances Halsband, FAIA|date=2 February 2007|work=The News of America's Community of Architects|access-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* U.S. Department of State Office of Foreign Buildings Operations Architectural Advisory Board - 1998-2003<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.docomomo-us.org/events/modernism-in-america-awards/2017-award-winners|title=Modernism in America Awards 2017 Winners|last=|first=|date=6 October 2017|website=DOCOMOMO|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":13\" />\n* Smith College, Architect Advisor to the Board of Trustees - 1998-2003<ref name=\":4\" />\n* U.S. General Services Administration National Register of Peer Professionals - 1998-2010<ref name=\":13\" />\n* ACSA, Northeast Regional Director - 1993-1995\n* Federal Reserve Bank Architectural Review Panel - 1993-2009<ref>{{Cite book|last=United States|first=General Services Administration|title=Dan M. Russell, Jr. United States Courthouse : Gulfport, Mississippi|publisher=U.S. General Services Administration, Public Buildings Service, Office of the Chief Architect, Center for Design Excellence and the Arts|year=2005|isbn=|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=30}}</ref>\n* AIA New York Chapter, President - 1992<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://nyrej.com/aia-new-york-leads-the-charge-to-amend-aia-code-of-ethics|title=AIA New York leads the charge to amend AIA Code of Ethics|date=6 November 2018|work=New York Real Estate Journal|access-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":13\" />\n* AIA New York Chapter Women in Architecture Leadership Network Founder - 1991<ref name=\":10\" />\n*[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]], Commissioner - 1984-1987<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":13\" />\n*[[New York State Council on the Arts]], Architecture Panel - 1980-1983<ref name=\":12\" />\n*[https://archleague.org The Architectural League of New York], (President 1985-1989) - 1975 - Present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archleague.org/about/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=|website=The Architectural League of New York|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Academic Appointments'''\n\n*[[University of Maryland, Baltimore|University of Maryland]], Kea Visiting Distinguished Professor - 2009<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arch.umd.edu/arch/kea-recipient/frances-halsband|title=Kea Professorship|last=|first=|date=2009|website=University of Maryland School of Architecture, Planning and Preservation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[University of Cincinnati]], Visiting Professor, Neihoff Studio - 2002<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bach|first=John|url=https://magazine.uc.edu/issues/1107/power.html|title=The Power of Place: Measuring the human impact of UC's architectural renaissance|date=November 2007|work=University of Cincinnati Magazine|access-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign]], Plym Professor - 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arch.illinois.edu/engagement/plym-distinguished-professors|title=Plym Distinguished Professors|last=Illinois|first=Architecture College of Fine & Applied Arts|date=|website=University of Illinois|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acsa-arch.org/tag/university-of-illinois-urbana-champaign/|title=The Illinois School of Architecture Appoints Suchi Reddy as the 2019 Plym Distinguished Visiting Professor|last=Sturges|first=Michelle|date=7 August 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n*[[Ball State University]], Emens Distinguished Professor - 1998-1999<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=A Time to Reflect|url=https://www.bsu.edu/-/media/WWW/DepartmentalContent/CAP/PDFs/recap/recap_2001_fall.pdf|journal=ReCap: College of Architecture and Planning|volume=|pages=20|via=Ball State University}}</ref>\n*[[University of California, Berkeley|University of California Berkeley]], Howard A. Friedman Visiting Professor - 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ced.berkeley.edu/give-to-ced/faculty-support/friedman-visiting-professorship|title=Friedman Visiting Professorship|last=|first=|date=|website=UC Berkeley|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Pratt Institute School of Architecture]], Dean - 1991-1994<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":14\" />\n*[[Columbia University]], Visiting Critic in Design - 1987<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Master Architect Series: R.M Kliment & Frances Halsband Architects|publisher=Images Publishing|year=2008|isbn=978-1-86470-1302|location=Australia|pages=}}</ref>\n*[[University of Pennsylvania]], Visiting Critic in Design - 1981<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://culturenow.org/cocktails_and_conversations&event=frances_halsband_and_michael_crosbie|title=Cocktails and Conversations Frances Halsband and Michael Crosbie|last=|first=|date=19 September 2014|website=Museum Without Walls|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Harvard University]], Visiting Critic in Design - 1980<ref name=\":15\" />\n*[[University of Virginia]], Visiting Critic in Design - 1979<ref name=\":15\" />\n*[[Rice University]], Visiting Critic in Design - 1979<ref name=\":15\" />\n*[[North Carolina State University]], Visiting Critic in Design - 1978<ref name=\":15\" />\n*[[Columbia University]], Visiting Critic in Design - 1975-1978<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n== Selected Publications ==\n\n=== Published Writings ===\n\n* \u201cNot a Park.\u201d In ''Maintaining: Public Works in the Next New York''. New York, NY: [[Urban Design Forum]], 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://urbandesignforum.org/programs/next-new-york/maintaining/|title=Book Launch {{!}} Maintaining: Public Works in the Next New York|last=Urban Design Forum|first=|date=8 July 2019|website=Urban Design Forum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cA Different Kind of Place,\u201d Faith & Form: The Interfaith Journal on Religion, Art, and Architecture, Vol. 52, No. 1, 2019<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halsband|first=Frances|date=2019|title=A Different Kind of Place|url=https://faithandform.com/feature/a-different-kind-of-place/|journal=Faith and Form: The Interfaith Journal on Religion, Art, and Architecture|volume=52|pages=|via=Faith and Form}}</ref>\n* \u201cReverence and Reconstruction,\u201d Faith & Form: The Interfaith Journal on Religion, Art, and Architecture, Vol. L, No. 2, 2017<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halsband|first=Frances|date=|title=Reverence and Reconstruction|url=https://faithandform.com/feature/reverence-and-reconstruction/|journal=Faith and Form The Interfaith Journal on Religion, Art, And Architecture|volume=50|pages=|via=Faith&Form}}</ref>\n* \u201cLiving and Learning: The Campus Redefined,\u201d [[The Chronicle of Higher Education]], April 28, 2006<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halsband|first=Frances|date=28 April 2006|title=Living and Learning: the Campus Redefined|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/LivingLearning-the/35803|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|volume=|pages=|via=The Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref>\n* \u201cCharles Klauder\u2019s Brilliant Invisible Hand.\u201d [[The Chronicle of Higher Education]], March 25, 2005<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halsband|first=Frances|date=25 March 2005|title=Charles Klauder's Brilliant Invisible Hand|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Charles-Klauders-Brilliant/2122|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|volume=|pages=|via=The Chronicle of Higher Education}}</ref>\n* \u201cCampuses in Place\u201d In Places Journal: Considering the Place of Campus'','' Vol. 17, Issue 1, Winter 2005<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halsband|first=Frances|date=Winter 2005|title=Campuses in Place|url=https://placesjournal.org/print-archive/considering-the-place-of-campus/?cn-reloaded=1|journal=Places Journal|volume=17|pages=|via=Places Journal}}</ref>\n* \"Introduction to The Inhabited Landscape: An Exhibition,\u201d Places Journal, Volume 4/4, 1988<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halsband|first=Frances|date=1988|title=Introduction to The Inhabited Landscape: An Exhibition|url=https://placesjournal.org/assets/legacy/pdfs/the-inhabited-landscape-introduction.pdf|journal=Places Journal|volume=4|pages=|via=Places Journal}}</ref>\n\n=== Illustrations ===\n\n* Halsband, Frances (Illustrator), ''Publishing: a writer's memoir,'' by Gail Godwin, Bloomsbury, 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/publishing-a-writers-memoir/oclc/907965981&referer=brief_results|title=Publishing: a writer's memoir|last=Godwin|first=Gail|date=2016|website=WorldCat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Halsband, Frances (Illustrator), \u201cUlster County Ghosts,\u201d by Gail Godwin, ''Kingston: The IBM Years,'' The Friends of Historic Kingston/Black Dome Press, Delmar NY, 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/kingston-the-ibm-years/oclc/878837609&referer=brief_results|title=Ulster County Ghosts|last=Godwin|first=Gail|date=2014|website=WorldCat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Halsband, Frances, illustrator, ''Evenings at Five'', by Gail Godwin, Ballantine Books, 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/evenings-at-five/oclc/216654863&referer=brief_results|title=Evenings at Five|last=Godwin|first=Gail|date=2003|website=WorldCat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://kliment-halsband.com/ Kliment Halsband Architects]\n*[https://clio.columbia.edu/catalog/12307197/ Kliment Halsband Architects records and architectural drawings, 1922-2007]. [http://library.columbia.edu/locations/avery/da.html/ Held by the Department of Drawings & Archives], [http://library.columbia.edu/locations/avery.html/ Avery Architectural & Fine Arts Library, Columbia University].\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Halsband, Frances}}\n[[Category:American women architects]]\n[[Category:Columbia Graduate School of Architecture, Planning and Preservation alumni]]\n[[Category:Swarthmore College alumni]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-architect-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American architect}}\n[[File:FrancesHalsband-square.jpg|thumb]]\n'''Frances Halsband''' FAIA (born October 30, 1943, in [[New York City]]) is an American architect and educator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arch.umd.edu/arch/kea-recipient/frances-halsband|title=Frances Halsband:  Kea Distinguished Professor in the Architecture program University of Maryland|last=|first=|date=Spring 2009|website=University of Maryland|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> She is a founder, with Robert Kliment, of [[Kliment Halsband Architects]], a New York City design firm widely recognized for preservation, adaptive reuse and master planning projects.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Woods|first=Lynn|url=https://hudsonvalleyone.com/2015/01/23/pioneering-architect-frances-halsband-got-her-start-on-woodstocks-village-green/|title=Pioneering architect Frances Halsband got her start on Woodstock\u2019s Village Green|date=23 January 2015|work=Hudson Valley One|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Significant works include The [[Brown University]] Framework for Physical Planning,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brown.edu/web/pae/documents/Institutional_Master_Plan_2006.pdf|title=Brown Master Plan Kliment Halsband Architects|last=|first=|date=30 March 2006|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> [[Long Island Rail Road|Long Island Railroad]] Entrance at 34 Street,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/01/08/realestate/postings-for-the-dashing-commuter-lirr-finishing-34th-st-pavilion.html|title=POSTINGS: For the Dashing Commuter|date=8 January 1995|work=The New York Times|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Visitor Center at [[Franklin D. Roosevelt Presidential Library and Museum|Franklin Roosevelt Presidential Library]],<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Hutton|first=Ann|url=https://hudsonvalleyone.com/2015/05/22/fdrs-hyde-park-hive-on-the-hudson/|title=FDRs Hyde Park Hive on the Hudson|date=22 May 2015|work=Hudson Valley One|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mount Sinai Health System|Mount Sinai]] Ambulatory Surgery Facility Kyabirwa Uganda.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Pintos|first=Paula|url=https://www.archdaily.com/928402/mount-sinai-kyabirwa-surgical-facility-kliment-halsband-architects|title=Mount Sinai Kyabirwa Surgical Facility Kliment Halsband Architects|date=December 2019|work=ArchDaily|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aiany.org/architecture/awards/2020-aiany-design-awards/|title=AIANY 2020 Design Awards Winners|last=|first=|date=January 2020|website=AIANY|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|last=Crosbie|first=Michael J|url=https://commonedge.org/new-york-architects-kliment-halsband-design-a-surgery-clinic-in-kyabirwa-uganda/|title=New York Architects Kliment Halsband Design A Surgery Clinic in Kyabirwa Uganda|date=25 November 2019|work=CommonEdge|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The firm received the AIA Firm Award in 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Architecture_Firm_Award&oldid=915263936|title=Architecture Firm Award Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=Wikipedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> and the New York AIA Medal of Honor in 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aia.org/awards/7276-architecture-firm-award|title=Architecture Firm Award|last=|first=|date=|website=AIANY|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1991 to 1994 Halsband was dean of the [[Pratt Institute School of Architecture|School of Architecture]] at [[Pratt Institute]],<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/08/15/arts/architecture-dean-named.html|title=Architecture Dean Named|date=15 August 1991|work=The New York Times|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|last=Wiseman|first=Carter|url=https://nymag.com/|title=A Dean of the Real|date=2 December 1991|work=New York Magazine|access-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and she has taught at [[Harvard University]],  [[Columbia University]], [[Rice University School of Architecture|Rice University]], [[University of Pennsylvania]], [[University of California, Berkeley]] and other institutions.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://commons.pratt.edu/mistressesofarchitecture/frances-halsband/|title=Pratt Mistresses of Architecture: Frances Halsband|last=|first=|date=Marc 2020|website=Pratt Mistresses of Pratt|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> She was the first woman president of [[American Institute of Architects|AIA New York]]<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://calendar.aiany.org/2018/11/05/leadership-breakfast-with-frances-halsband-faia/|title=Leadership Breakfast with Frances Halsband|last=|first=|date=8 February 2019|website=AIANY Calendar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> and The Architectural League of New York.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|last=Gamolina|first=Julia|url=https://www.madamearchitect.org/interviews/2020/3/11/frances-halsband|title=Power to Move Forward: Frances Halsband on Giving Back, Staying in Touch, and Ethical Behavior|date=11 March 2020|work=Madame Architect|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She is a former commissioner of the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission|New York City Landmarks Commission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dna.bwaf.org/architect/halsband-frances|title=Beverly Willis Architecture Foundation: Frances Halsband|last=|first=|date=|website=Beverly Willis Architecture Foundation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|last=Hoechstetter|first=Marissa|url=https://msmagazine.com/2018/11/02/fellowship-leadership-fighting-sexual-harassment-architecture/|title=Fellowship is Leadership: Fighting Sexual Harassment in Architecture|date=2 November 2018|work=Ms. Magazine|access-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018 Halsband lead a successful effort to amend the AIA Code of Ethics<ref name=\":13\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aia.org/pages/3296-code-of-ethics-and-professional-conduct|title=AIA Code of Ethics|last=|first=|date=|website=AIA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> to prohibit harassment or discrimination and commit to fostering a professional environment of mutual respect and equity.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Post|first=Nadine M|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/46169-lighting-a-fire-under-the-aia-in-a-crusade-against-all-types-of-workplace-abuse|title=Lighting a Fire Under the AIA in a Crusade Against All Types of Workplace Abuse|date=10 January 2019|work=Engineering News Record|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Budds|first=Diana|url=https://www.curbed.com/2019/8/5/20699746/architecture-sexual-harrassment-aia-ethics-code|title=Inside the AIA\u2019s efforts to address #MeToo|date=5 August 2019|work=Curbed|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  In recognition of this effort she was named one of [[Engineering News-Record]] (ENR) Top 25 Newsmakers.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2019 she received an Honorary Doctor of Design from the [[NewSchool of Architecture and Design|NewSchool of Architecture San Diego]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://network.aia.org/cof/home/executivecommittee|title=Network AIA: Executive Committee|last=|first=|date=|website=Network AIA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life & Education ==\nShe received her B.A. at [[Swarthmore College]] in 1965 and a Master's from [[Columbia University]] in 1968.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www2.arch.uiuc.edu/organizations/wia/disprofs/halsbandfrances.html |title=\"Women in Architecture\" at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign |access-date=2008-06-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829000641/http://www2.arch.uiuc.edu/organizations/wia/disprofs/halsbandfrances.html |archive-date=2008-08-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>Lorenz, Clare, Women in Architecture: a contemporary perspective,  Rizzoli,  New York,  1990 p. 44</ref>  She has served on juries for design awards, chaired the 1999 [[American Institute of Architects]] Committee on Design, and served as [[Center for Architecture|AIA New York's]] first woman president in 1991.<ref>[http://www.aia.org/aiarchitect/thisweek07/0202/0202dp.cfm AIA Profile]</ref><ref>https://www.aiany.org/news/aiany-supported-resolution-leads-to-important-changes-to-aia-code-of-ethics/</ref> Halsband and Kliment were married in 1971 in Woodstock New York.\u00a0Their son, Alexander Halsband Kliment was born in 1979. They made their home in New York City and Woodstock New York.<ref name=\":0\" /> Kliment retired from KHA in 2013, and passed away in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Martin|first=Olivia|url=https://archpaper.com/2017/06/robert-kliment-cofounder-kliment-halsband/|title=Robert Kliment, cofounder of Kliment Halsband Architects, has passed|date=9 January 2017|work=The Architect's Newspaper|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Professional Practice ==\n\n*[[Kliment Halsband Architects]], New York, NY - 2008-Present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kliment-halsband.com/studio-history/|title=Studio History|last=|first=|date=|website=Kliment Halsband Architects|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n* R.M.Kliment & Frances Halsband Architects, New York, NY - 1978-2008\n* R.M.Kliment Architect, New York, NY - 1972-1977\n*[[Mitchell/Giurgola|Mitchell/Giurgola Architects]], New York, NY -1968-1972<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Selected Projects ===\n''This selection is specific to projects for which Halsband has been principally responsible''\n\n* [[Arcadia University, Pennsylvania|Arcadia University]] Commons, Glenside, PA (2012)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cropper|first=Purnell|url=https://www.arcadia.edu/news/2010/04/architect-includes-geothermal-wells-walking-bridge-commons-design|title=Architect Includes Geothermal Wells, Walking Bridge in Commons Design|date=23 April 2010|work=Arcadia University News|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Arcadia University, Pennsylvania|Arcadia University]] Landman Library, Glenside, PA (2003)<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=AIArchitects|url=http://info.aia.org/aiarchitect/thisweek05/tw0401/0401libraryawards.htm|title=Eight Beautiful Buildings Win 2005 Library Awards|date=April 2005|work=AIArchitects|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Avalon Morningside Park|Avalon Morningside]] at the [[Cathedral of St. John the Divine]], New York, NY (2008)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Horsley|first=Carter|url=https://www.cityrealty.com/nyc/morningside-heights/avalon-morningside-park-1-morningside-drive/review/44851|title=Avalon Morningside Park, 1 Morningside Drive|date=|work=City Realty|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Brown University]] Strategic Framework for Physical Planning, Providence, RI (2003/2009)<ref name=\":2\" />\n* [[Dartmouth College]] Roth Center for Jewish Life, Hanover, NH (1998)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Slating|first=Peter|date=September 1993|title=SCOOP|url=https://usmodernist.org/AIANY/AIANY-1993-09.pdf|journal=Oculus|volume=56|pages=3|via=US Modernist}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rtmudge.com/awards/|title=Architecture Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=Randall T Mudge and Associates|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Friends Seminary]], New York, NY (2019)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pintos|first=Paula|url=https://www.archdaily.com/935714/friends-seminary-school-kliment-halsband-architects?ad_source=search&ad_medium=search_result_all|title=Friends Seminary / Kliment Halsband Architects|date=March 2020|work=ArchDaily|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Lentz|first=Linda C|url=https://www.architecturalrecord.com/articles/14450-friends-seminary-by-kliment-halsband-architects|title=Friends Seminary by Kliment Halsband Architects|date=February 2020|work=Architectural Record|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Johns Hopkins University]] Gilman Hall, Baltimore, MD (2010)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seward|first=Aaron|url=https://archpaper.com/2010/10/gilman-hall-at-johns-hopkins-university/|title=Gilman Hall at Johns Hopkins University|date=27 October 2010|work=The Architect's Newspaper|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Long Island Rail Road|Long Island Railroad]] Entrance at [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Pennsylvania Station]], New York, NY (1994)<ref name=\":3\" />\n* [[Mount Sinai Health System|Mount Sinai]] Ambulatory Surgery Facility Kyabirwa Uganda, Africa (2019)<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" />\n* [[University of Chicago]] Neubauer Collegium for Culture and Society, Chicago, IL (2015)<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.aiachicago.org/dea_archive/2015/university-of-chicago-neubauer-collegium-for-culture-and-society1/|title=University of Chicago Neubauer Collegium|date=2015|work=AIA Chicago|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] South College, Amherst, MA (2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umass.edu/cp/south-college|title=South College|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Massachusetts Amherst|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Franklin D. Roosevelt Presidential Library and Museum|Franklin D. Roosevelt Presidential Library]] Henry A. Wallace Visitor and Education Center, Hyde Park, NY (2004)<ref name=\":4\" />\n* [[Zen Mountain Monastery]] Sangha House, Mt. Tremper, NY (2013)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halsband|first=Frances|date=|title=A Different Kind of Place|url=https://faithandform.com/feature/a-different-kind-of-place/|journal=Faith and Form|volume=52|pages=|via=www.faithandform.com}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Achievements ==\n\n=== Honors ===\n\n* Honorary Doctor of Design, [[NewSchool of Architecture and Design]] - 2019<ref name=\":11\" />\n* [[Engineering News-Record|Engineering News Record]] 2018 Top 25 Newsmaker - 2019<ref name=\":1\" />\n* AIA Firm Award, R.M.Kliment & Frances Halsband Architects - 1998<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Architecture_Firm_Award&oldid=915263936|title=Architecture Firm Award|last=|first=|date=|website=Wikipedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n* AIA New York Medal of Honor, R.M.Kliment & Frances Halsband Architects - 1997<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://46u0j30o449zq8181dfurbcj-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/AIA-New-York-Chapter-Awards-History-as-of-10_2017.pdf|title=R.M. Kliment & Frances Halsband Architects|last=|first=|date=|website=AIA New York Chapter Awards History|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aiany.org/membership/join/chapter-recognition/|title=Chapter Recognition|last=|first=|date=|website=AIANY|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Fellow of the American Institute of Architects]] - 1986\n\n=== Civic & Professional Boards ===\n\n* AIA [https://www.aia.org/pages/6075263-college-of-fellows College of Fellows] Executive Committee - 2019-Present<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aia.org/pages/6075263-college-of-fellows|title=College of Fellows Leadership|last=Halsband|first=Frances|date=|website=American Institute of Architects|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Castellana|first=John|date=13 August 2019|title=Welcome Frances Halsband, FAIA!|url=https://issuu.com/aiacollegeoffellows/docs/cof_newsletter_august_2019_draft|journal=The AIA College of Fellows Newsletter|volume=|pages=17|via=ISSUU}}</ref>\n* [[Harvard University]], Design Review Panel - 2005-2009<ref name=\":9\" />\n* [[Byrdcliffe Colony|Woodstock Byrdclif